TikTok is hiding unwanted videos from users
According to TikTok, the number of its users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under 18 years old.
This is Imagine China / Reuters
Chinese social network TikTok censors videos that mention Tiananmen Square, Tibetan independence or the banned religious group Falun Gong, The Guardian reports.
Documents obtained by the publication say that the owner of TikTok (the company ByteDance) uses the application to promote China's foreign policy goals abroad.
The bulk of the violations related to China's policies fall under "incitement to hate".
In each case, TikTok places objectionable posts in context that fits the general guidelines, so that the social network's actions do not appear censored.
For example, the ban on criticism of China's socialist system falls under the general ban on "criticism or attacks on the politics and social rules of any country, such as constitutional monarchy, parliamentary system, etc".
Banning references to the Tiananmen Square incident or the Cambodian genocide falls under "distorting the history of China or other countries".
The document also lists the names of twenty "foreign leaders or statesmen", including North Korean leaders Kim Jong-il, Kim Il-sung and Kim Jong-un, Indian politician Mahatma Gandhi, US presidents Donald Trump and Barack Obama, Japanese Prime Minister Shinzo Abe, South Korean President Park Geun-hye, Indonesian President Joko Widodo and Indian Prime Minister Narendra Modi, the document said.
The forbidden material is divided into two categories, the document says.
Posts from the first category are deleted by the administrators of the social network and may lead to the blocking of the user.
Less serious violations fall into the second category: such posts remain on the site, but their distribution is limited by TikTok's algorithms.
ByteDance told The Guardian that the rules are outdated and no longer applicable: "We now use a localised approach to moderation and also involve independent local experts".
Russian TikTok users have no specific restrictions on posting, says Rustem Bogdanov, co-founder of the "Producer Center".
Producer Center is one of the Russian media companies that officially cooperates with TikTok.
All advertising materials of bloggers "Producer Center" is agreed with representatives of the social network, but user materials can be posted without agreement, reports Bogdanov.
Asked if it is possible to comment on politics or Putin on TikTok, Bogdanov replied in the affirmative and said he had seen similar posts.
Roman Zaripov, the founder of Our Didgital, agrees with Bogdanov: "The basic rules for TikTok users are listed in the user agreement: you can't post shocking content, discriminatory statements, and so on".
But under these rules, any content that does not please the moderators can be included, Zaripov notes.
Zaripov's agency is another Russian partner of TikTok.
According to TikTok, the number of its users worldwide exceeds 500 million, 40% of whom are under 18 years old.
According to the user agreement, only people over 13 years old can use TikTok.
The social network administrators check their age using artificial intelligence: the neural network analyzes faces and determines how old a person looks, Bogdanov says.
If the neural network decides that a user is underage, his account may be deleted, he adds.
According to RBC, in September 2019, ByteDance opened an office in Moscow on the territory of WeWork coworking.
