Expert says why you should avoid tea bags
A team of scientists from Canada, representing McGill University, found that when a tea bag is brewed in a cup, over ten billion microplastics are ingested in five minutes.
Particles of sawdust can also be added to packaged beverages, food safety expert Yelizaveta Tikhonova told Nation News.
According to the agronomist, the consumer cannot get reliable information about the composition of the packaged tea - the producer may add ingredients that will not be indicated on the package.
They don't throw away sawdust at the end of the season, so they can end up in the tea.
"Moreover, tea plants are not always included in the packets", said Tikhonova.
She says that it is better to avoid the drink and instead drink the tea that is sold in specialized shops.
She also stressed that the danger of packaged tea lies not only in its composition but also in its production method - the micro-particles are heated to high temperatures, which can cause them to release harmful substances.
"The best thing to do is to buy pure green or black tea, which has the least amount of additives", said the expert.
