The Russian government has estimated that deliveries of agricultural products and foodstuffs to Russia from countries that have been subject to the Russian food embargo have decreased by more than 100 times since 2013.
According to a report sent to Russian President Vladimir Putin, in the first half of 2019, 31 thousand tons of products were imported from sanctioned countries, compared to 3 million 442.2 thousand tons in the same period in 2013, Interfax reports.
At the same time, the value of imported products decreased to $ 226.5 million from $ 4 billion 975.5 million respectively.
We're talking about the supply of goods that didn't fall under the embargo.
As the report indicates, the decreased volumes of prohibited imports were compensated by increased imports from the CIS countries, Africa, Southeast Asia, Serbia.
Recall that in late August, the government extended until December 31, 2020 the rules for the destruction of agricultural products, raw materials and food, which are prohibited to import into Russia as part of counter-sanctions.
The document, posted on the official legal information portal, noted that the validity of the rules has been extended for another year - from 31 December 2019 to 31 December 2020.
Initially, the decree on the abolition of sanctions applied to products from the USA, EU, Australia, Norway and Canada.
Later, on August 13, 2015, Albania, Montenegro, Iceland, Liechtenstein were "joined" to this list, and on January 1, 2016 - Ukraine.
Putin's decree to destroy the "sanctions" (food embargoes imposed by Moscow in response to Western anti-Russian sanctions) that were illegally imported into the country came into force in 2015.
In turn, the government allowed the destruction of "sanctioned" food by any legal means.
As Western sanctions persisted, the Russian Federation also extended its response.
However, this does not apply to products that are imported for personal use.
The ban does not apply to goods for personal consumption weighing less than 5 kilograms.
However, the head of the Council under the President of the Russian Federation for the Development of Civil Society and Human Rights, Mikhail Fedotov, had earlier called the destruction of food "simply immoral", and this, according to him, negatively affects the education of people.
Moreover, the initiative to ban the destruction of food products suitable for consumption was taken by Rospotrebnadzor in early June.
After that, the Council for Human Rights under the President of the Russian Federation gave a similar recommendation to the government.
And Russian Deputy Prime Minister Alexei Gordeev said that destroying food is wrong, and we need to think about how to use it for its intended purpose, assessing its quality.
Firm manager found guilty of tax evasion
By the verdict of the Leninsky district court of the city of Cheboksara, the director of the LLC "Land and right" Vyacheslav Morozov was found guilty of committing crimes provided for in the paragraph "b" of article 2 of article 199 of the RF Criminal Code (avoidance of paying taxes from the organization by including in the tax declaration deliberately false information, committed in a particularly large amount) and part 2 of article 327 of the RF Criminal Code (making an official document granting rights and releasing from obligations, in order to use it, committed with the purpose of concealing another crime and facilitating its commission).
This is reported by the press service of the Investigative Committee of the Russian Federation in Chuvashia.
From January 2008 to December 2009, Vyacheslav Morozov entered into the documents of the tax accounting of the LLC information about incomplete transactions.
According to the fictitious documents, the company incurred additional costs, and, therefore, the amount of taxes to be paid on the value added and on the profit of the organization was reduced by 11.2 million rubles.
Vyacheslav Morozov has been sentenced to 3.5 years of probation.
First school of new format to open in 2023
A new school will be opened in Khamovniki.
According to the head of Moskomstroyinvest Anastasia Pyatova, there will create all conditions for self-realization and development of children's talents.
The name of the educational institution was "New Look".
This project will be supervised by the Moscow State Institute of International Relations of the Russian Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Fund "Economic Development of the Higher School".
The 10,000-square-foot building is scheduled to begin construction next year.
The building will be completed by the end of 2022, and the first students will be enrolled next year.
"The project envisages the creation of a public, non-commercial educational space, which will be based on the traditions of the classical Moscow school and experimental methods", - said in the press service of Moskomstroyinvest.
Chile is building a 1 billion euro telescope
This is reported by TASS with reference to the press service of the European Southern Observatory (ESO).
As ESO reports, this week the construction of the dome of the building that will house the E-ELT (European Extremely Large Telescope), the most expensive and ambitious ground-based astronomy project to date, has officially begun.
The total cost of the ESO is estimated to be over one billion euros.
Most of this money will be spent on the equipment and construction of the observatory building.
The most expensive and complex component of the telescope is its record-breaking mirror, which will be about 120 feet [39 m] in diameter.
It will be assembled from 798 hexagonal segments measuring 1.4 meters.
This huge mirror, along with two auxiliary reflective surfaces, each 14 and 12 feet (4.2 and 3.75 m) in diameter, will help the E-ELT to obtain the first detailed images of planets outside our solar system, stars in other galaxies, and to search for Earth-like planets.
In addition, scientists will try to use the observatory to observe the vicinity of Sgr A*, a supermassive black hole at the center of the Milky Way.
Although the dome has only just begun, scientists, engineers, and other experts have been working on the mirrors, scientific instruments, and other components of the observatory for three years - since the first plans for the E-ELT were announced.
The contract for the main mirror, which cost about 400 million euros, was awarded to the German company SCHOTT and the French company Safran Reosc.
